media_caption: Turnsout, the 127 stylized human and animal figures (frogs and lizards) engraved on the rockwall dated back to 3000 BC. Along with other designs that may have depicted other interesting figures, erosion may have caused it to deteriorate.
text_description: Humans use a rock shelter in Binangonan, Rizal where they make carvings on the rock surface, now called the Angono petroglyph. They are dated to the Neolithic period.
Humans leave handprints at Alab, Mountain Province.
Kalanay-type pottery, named after Kalanay Cave in Aroroy, northwest Masbate, is made.
Wood carving and weaving are introduced to the Philippines.
The Malay forge is developed, which is essential for forging metal used in making implements.
Development of boat building in SEAsia is documented to this time.
European colonization of territories outside Europe begins and spreads European architectural traditions worldwide.

Ferdinand Magellan encounters bamboo and thatch dwellings of the Cebuano. Antonio de Pigafetta, the chronicler of Magellan, records how the Cebuanos lived and their practices and customs. His is the first European account of a Cebuano village. Photo: Portrait of Ferdinand Magellan by Charles Legrand.

The Boholano inhabitants abandon dwellings resting on stout wooden piles over the shallows of the Panglao Strait. In Dapitan, they build their village under the protective shelter of Ilihan Hill, which they fortify.
May 8: Miguel Lopez de Legazpi founds the Ciudad Santisimo Nombre de Jesus at the site named Sug-bu. A triangular palisade is built to protect the ciudad.

The Augustinians, who accompanied Miguel Lopez de Legazpi, establish the Convento of Santisimo Nombre de Jesus (aka Santo Niño). They build the first Catholic church and priory complex in the Philippines.
The temporary Church of Santisimo Rosario in Binondo is built by the Dominicans for the Chinese Christians under their ministry.
Far Eastern University, Manila, is completed in Art Deco.
In preparation for Limahong’s attack, Manila is surrounded with a makeshift wall made of whatever material was found suitable, like barrels, wooden palisades, sacks of sand and gravel.

Frs Juan de Plasencia and Diego de Oropesa OFM found the towns in Laguna and Tayabas, where they build churches of light material. Like these churches, the structures built in Manila and in the newly established missions are of wood, bamboo, and thatch. These materials characterize church construction from the late 1500 to the mid-1600.

media_caption: A sketch of the first Cathedral of Manila destroyed by an earthquake (Intramuros Administration, Repro by Nilo jorge Parrilla, 5 October 1992)
text_description: First Manila Cathedral is completed. The temporary church of wood and thatch, built by secular priest Juan de Vivero, is destroyed by the fire of 1583. (Photo from Intramuros Administration)

media_caption: First Bishop of Manila, born in Rioja , Spain in 1512.
text_description: Bp Domingo de Salazar OP resides in a temporary house of bamboo and nipa. He uses the church of 1579 as a cathedral.
The first Manila Cathedral is burnt and replaced by a provisional structure.
Antonio Sedeño is actively involved in construction in Manila from 1581 to 1595.
Fr Diego de Moxica OSA builds a convento of stone in Pasig before he dies this year.
Gov-Gen Santiago de Vera requires all buildings in Manila to be built of stone.
Jan 1: The first Dominican church in Intramuros is completed, a provisional structure of light material begun on 6 Aug 1587.
Gov-Gen Gomez Perez Dasmariñas begins improving the fortification of Manila.
The second Manila Cathedral, now made of stone is completed in 1591 but destroyed by earthquake in 1600.
An ivory image of the Santisimo Rosario, made by a Chinese convert in Manila, is enshrined in the Dominican church in Intramuros.
A palisade is built at La Caldera (Recodo), Zamboanga.
The Colegio de Santa Potenciana building behind San Agustin church is completed. It is a boarding school for girls.
Sep 1: Fr Antonio Sedeño, who is credited with introducing Hispanic traditions of building in the Philippines, dies in Cebu.
The Colegio de Manila buildings, consisting of a residence and a school, are constructed in Intramuros.
A provisional church in Butuan is completed by Ledesma.
The Colegio de Manila in Intramuros is damaged by earthquake.

media_caption: Church of Santa Catalina de Alejandria in Carcar, Cebu, 2003
media_credit: Photo by Betty Lalana and Lino Arboleda, Ortigas Foundation Library Collection
text_description: Augustinians build a church at Siaro (Carcar, Cebu).
The Lal-lo church in Cagayan Valley is built by the Dominicans around this time.

article_title: Architecture 1602 Nuestra Señora de los  Angeles
text_description: The Nuestra Señora de los Angeles, mother church of the Franciscans, is built in Intramuros.

media_caption: St. John the Baptist Church, Taytay, Rizal exterior 3. Taken 11 May 2014.
text_description: Church of San Juan Bautista, Taytay, begun in 1600, is completed. Photo: St John the Baptist Church in Taytay, Rizal, 2014 (Urbanroamer)
San Miguel church at Isla de Provisor on the Pasig burns. The mission’s administration is transferred to the Jesuits.

media_caption: The Recollect church and convent at Bagumbayan.
text_description: Being late comers, the Recollects build their church and convent outside the walls at Bagumbayan. However, the Recollects are able to occupy a 12,000 square meter lot at the southeast corner of Intramuros. It has a pipe organ built by Diego Cera OAR. The church was destroyed in 1945. (Photo from The Augustinian Recollect Gallery)
Dominicans finish rebuilding their church in Intramuros strong enough to support a stone vault after the roof of an earlier church caught fire in 1603.
The third Manila Cathedral, also of stone, is completed at the initiative of Abp Miguel de Benavides, OP. In 1645, it is destroyed by earthquake.

media_caption: Parish church of the neighborhood of Binondo, Manila, in the Spanish magazine El Museo Universal. 18 January 1868.
text_description: The stone church of the Santisimo Rosario in Binondo is built. By the 18th century, it is replaced by a well-built church designed by Domingo de la Cruz Gonzales.
A bastioned stone fort replaces Fort San Pedro in Iloilo. It is demolished by the Americans in the early 20th century.
Because it is exposed to slave raids, the village of Siaro is transferred in land to Carcar or Cabcar and the old town name forgotten.

article_title: Architecture 1620 Jesuit church in Buenavista hill
text_description: The Jesuit novitiate and church, dedicated to San Pedro, are completed on Buenavista hill, overlooking the Pasig River. In 1622, the novices occupy the building. The church still stands, renamed as the Parish of San Pedro.
Malabon church nave is constructed. A transept is added in 1835; the facade is renovated in 1861, with the addition of a Greek temple-type façade by Arch. Luciano Oliver.
Jesuits build a church and residence at the Marikina hacienda.
The Augustinian’s Guadalupe Monastery in Makati is completed; it is damaged during WWII and rebuilt in 1970.
A fort is constructed in Catbalogan, Samar, behind the Church of San Bartolome.
The Colegio de San Ildefonso, designed by Campioni, and the Church of Nuestra Señora de Loreto at Cavite Puerto (Cavite City) are inaugurated.
The first church of Dapitan, probably made of stone, is built with the assistance of the descendants of Datu Pagbuya, Pedro Manuel Manoc (Mano-oc).
Nov 30: The Manila Cathedral built by Benavides is destroyed during the earthquake.

After the 1645 earthquake, a hybrid architecture (arquitectura mestiza) develops, which replaces the stone vaults of European architecture with a lighter roof of timber and thatch, eventually replaced by terra cotta tiles. The structure has a lower story of stone and an upper story of wood.
The stone cathedral of Nueva Segovia (Lal-lo), Cagayan Valley, begun in 1653, is completed. Damaged in 1719, it is replaced by a temporary church in 1721.
Ignacio Alzina, SJ describes Philippine colonial houses as “arquitectura mestiza,” hybrid structures of stone for the ground floor and wood for the upper floors.
Ternate church, Cavite, is built in honor of the Santo Niño. Ternate is populated by Christianized Merdekas who leave Ternate, Indonesia for Cavite, when the Spanish garrison is closed.
Tanauan church in Leyte is completed. The church is fortified with a perimeter wall and bastions.
The fourth Manila Cathedral, begun in 1659 by Abp Miguel de Poblete (r. 1653-1667), is completed under Abp Diego Camacho (r. 1697-1705).
Indang’s Church of San Gregorio Magno in Cavite is built around this year.
San Mateo Church of Nuestra Señora de Aranzazu in Rizal is completed.
Palo Church of La Transfiguracion del Señor and the Abuyog Church of San Francisco Xavier, both in Leyte, are completed.
Church of the Venerable Tercera Orden (VOT) is built perpendicular to the Francisan church of Nuestra Señora de los Angeles in Intramuros.
Before this year, a fortification is built on Ilihan Hill, Dapitan.
The Falsabraga de Santa Catalina in Fort Santiago, Manila, is built.
Casa Ordaveza in Majayjay, Laguna is constructed.
Sariaya’s Church of Santa Cruz in Laguna is completed at a new site, the same one the town of Sariaya presently occupies.

The Alcaiceria de San Fernando in Binondo, designed by Fr. Lucas de Jesus Maria, is completed. It is an octagonal building, which serves as the silk market and temporary residence of traders from south China.
The Palapag Church of San Ignacio and its fortress in Samar is built around this year.
Fort Nuestra Señora del Triunfo y de la Victoria is completed in Misamis (Ozamis City) by Jose Ducos, SJ.
Silay is fortified with a palisade.
The stone Church of San Bartolome in Catbalogan, Samar is completed before this year.
Casa de España, aka Casino Español and the S. Villanueva Bldg are constructed in Iloilo.

media_caption:
Depiction of the Visayan pintados, ca 1590

(Change source)
media_credit: Photo from Boxer Codex, The Lilly Library Digital Collections
text_description: British troops ransack Intramuros. Many works of art and precious objects are destroyed and documents destroyed or looted. Among those believed to have been looted is the Boxer Codex, which has 16th century illustrations of native Filipinos, like the Visayan (in photo). (Boxer Codex, The Lilly Library Digital Collections)

As a result of the Jesuits’ expulsion, some churches and buildings remain abandoned. New administrators are assigned to these places, who in time will repair and renovate the buildings, in some cases obliterating or obscuring the Jesuit heritage.

Some churches in Samar are abandoned for about a decade until the Franciscans take charge in 1804. Recollects take over Bohol and western Mindanao. The diocesan or secular clergy of Manila take charge of Cavite and Marinduque.
The Archbishop of Manila takes over the abandoned Jesuit college building and adjoining church in Intramuros and uses them for a seminary.
The fourth Manila Cathedral is completed. As result of the 1749 Taal eruption, the cathedral is deemed unsafe and is demolished in 1751.
Puerta Real, formerly at the end of Calle Real del Palacio, is transferred toward the west facing the walls of Colegio de San Jose to improve Intramuros’ defensive capability.
The Cuartel de Santa Lucia, along the western flank of Intramuros is constructed, following the plans of Tomas Sanz, as the barracks for the Artelleria de la Montaña.
A new Church in Taal, Batangas, built near the Caysasay shrine and begun in 1756, is completed by Martin Aguirre, OSA. The Taal eruption of 1852 will damage the church and convento.
Times Theater in Quiapo, designed by Luis Ma. Araneta, is completed.
Malaspina’s artists Brambila and Ravenat illustrate principal buildings in Manila, leaving a visual record of what these buildings look like after the British occupation.

article_title: Architecture 1810 Santa Maria church, Ilocos Sur
text_description: Santa Maria Church in Ilocos Sur is completed. It is declared a World Heritage site in 1993.
Puente de Aritao, aka Puente Antigua and Puente Munting Bayan, in Tayabas, Quezon, is built of stone under Gov Diego Urbino.

The Manila Cathedral’s vault collapses, while the cathedral canons are gathered for the Vespers on the Eve of Corpus Christi. Among the casualties is Pablo Pelaez, a diocesan priest noted for his brillance, leadership and advocacy of the rights of the diocesan clergy, most of whom are native Filipinos or mestizos.
The Maxino residence in Unisan, Quezon is completed.
The Clarin house in Loay, Bohol is built; it is named after the family of Aniceto Velez Clarin, gov of Bohol from 1901 to 1904.

Naga’s Cathedral of San Juan, in Camarines Sur, begun at the initiative of Bp Bernardo de la Concepcion, OFM in 1808, is completed. It is restored in 1890, and then again in 1987-1988 under Abp. Leonardo Legazpi, OP.
Silay’s grand ancestral houses are built around this time as a result of the economic upturn brought by the production of sugar for export.
A granite staircase known as Hagdan-hagdan, later renamed San Lorenzo Ruiz steps, connecting the Taal Basilica with the shrine to Our Lady of Caysasay, is built under Fr. Celestino Mayordomo.

media_caption: Church and convento of San Geronimo in Morong, Rizal, 2014
text_description: The facade of Morong’s Church of San Geronimo in Rizal, designed by Bartolome Palatino of Paete and begun in 1850, is completed. Photo: Morong church and convento, 2014 (Mariano Sayno)

As a result of the opening of the Iloilo international port, Iloilo grows rapidly and large bahay na bato are built in the area between the Church of San Jose and Fort San Pedro. Photo: Prewar view of Iloilo City (Leo Cloma Collection)
The sixth Manila Cathedral is completed. The sixth cathedral will collapse during the earthquake of 1863.
Villa Angela in Vigan built.

article_title: Architecture 1859 Capel of San Vicente Ferrer
text_description: Chapel of San Vicente Ferrer, in Barangay Cogon, Carcar, Cebu is built.

The Tayabas Church of San Miguel in Laguna is completed, after extensive renovation and expansion under Fr. Benito de la Pila OFM, begun in 1856. The church is raised to a basilica minore in 1988 and declared a historical landmark in 1972 and 1986 by NHI.
Puerta de Isabel II, the last gate of Intramuros to be built, is completed, replacing Magallanes, a small gate that leads to the Pasig River.

media_caption: Church of Santo Domingo in Intramuros, Manila, ca 1910
text_description: The fifth Santo Domingo church, begun 1864, is completed. It is designed by European-trained Felix Arroyo Roxas Sr in Neogothic style. It is destroyed on 21 Dec 1941 by Japanese bombs.
The Tetuan Church of San Ignacio in Zamboanga is built.
La Paz Church of Nuestra Señora de la Paz y Buenviaje in Iloilo is completed. It is rebuilt after World War II.
The “Gift House” in Taal, Batangas is built by Eulalio Villavicencio for his bride, Gliceria Marella, hence the popular name.
The Dakong Balay heritage house in Carcar, Cebu is renovated around this time. It is acquired by the Noel family from a previous owner. It is declared heritage house by NHI in Sept 2009.

article_title: Architecture 1876 Parian church of San Juan Bautista
text_description: Parian church of San Juan Bautista in Cebu, built by the mestizo Chinese diocesan clergy early in the century, is demolished. After a long drawn conflict with the convent of Santo Niño over jurisdiction, the parish of San Juan is ordered disbanded and demoted to a visita under Santo Niño.
The Jesuit church and residence in Jolo are built inside Jolo’s walled settlement.
Teatro Filipino at Echague in Quiapo is built.
The Sagrario (side chapel) beside Manila Cathedral is damaged and is never rebuilt.

The Carriedo Municipal Waterworks begins to conduct water to Manila. Begun in 1867, it was designed by Genaro Palacios and financed from investments made on a 10,000 peso bequest by Manila governor Francisco de Carriedo y Peredo in 1734. Photo: Carriedo Fountain, part of the Carriedo Waterworks System, built in May 1882 (Photo from NHCP)
Santa Catalina College in Intramuros is rebuilt. Photo: Music room of Santa Catalina College, 1887 (Photo from John Tewell)
The Pedro Singson residence in Vigan is completed. This ancestral house is preserved as Vigan Heritage Mansion Hotel.

Ermita’s Church of Nuestra Señora de Guia is completed, designed by Lorenzo Guerrero. The church is destroyed during World War II and a new church is built in the 1950s, designed by Carlos Antonio Santos-Viola.

The third Ayuntamiento, also known as Casas Consistoriales or Cabildo (Manila’s City Hall), in Intramuros is most likely completed after this year. Various architects work on this building, namely: Eduardo Lopez Navarro, Felix A, Roxas Sr, and Juan Hervas.
Surigao Church is built.

The second San Ignacio, begun in 1879, is completed. It is designed by Felix Roxas Sr. in the Neoclassical and Neorennaisance styles. Sculptures are made by Isabelo Tampinco and his workshop. Photo: Facade of the 1889 San Ignacio Church (René B. Javellana Collection)

The Recollects complete the all-steel San Sebastian church in Quiapo, designed by Genaro Palacios. It uses prefabricated steel parts imported from Europe. Photo: Facade and side view of the all-steel neo-Gothic San Sebastian Church (Philippine Picture Post Cards: 1900-1920 by Jonathan Best, The Bookmark, Inc, 1994)
Church of Santa Rita at Balingasag, Misamis Oriental is constructed.
The church at Las Mercedes, Zamboanga is completed around this year.
With Paula de Sanchez, Jose Rizal builds a relief map of Mindanao in the Dapitan plaza.
The Escuela de Niños y Niñas in Dapitan, Zamboanga del Norte, is completed around this year.
Tamontaka Church in Cotabato is built.
American soldiers open the first primary school of the American public school system at the site of the Alcaiceria de San Fernando in Binondo. The school is named Primary School of San Nicolas.
US military camps are set up in Malate at sites whose streets will be named after the different states from which soldiers have been recruited, like Pennsylvania, Vermont, Colorado, and Nebraska.
The Philippine School of Arts and Trade (now TUP) is built in the Mission Revival style.
Benitez Hall and Malcolm Hall at the UP Diliman campus, both designed by Juan Arellano, are completed.

Iloilo’s casa real, built in 1840, is named the Iloilo Provincial Capitol. Renovated, it is used as a Japanese garrison during World War II. It is repaired in the 1960s but damaged by fire in 1998. It is declared a historical site in 2010 and restored by NHCP. Photo: Iloilo Provincial Capitol, ca 1915 (Nereo Cajilig Lujan Collection)
Edgar Bourne completes the Custom house in Manila, a wooden building with a dome.

Edgar Bourne builds a wooden city hall for Manila, based on elements of the bahay na bato. He also builds the Government Laboratory in the Mission Revival style using masonry joined by cement and lime mortar.

American architect and city planner Daniel H. Burnham (in photo) arrives in the Philippines upon the invitation of Com. William Cameron Forbes. He tours Manila and Baguio to prepare plans for the capital city and the “hill station,” Baguio.

To open access to the wharfs along the Pasig River, the wall at the end of Calle Real del Palacio, the Bastion de Santo Domingo and its gate, the Almacenes, Maestranza walls from Fort Santiago to San Juan de Letran are demolished.
The Liloan Lighthouse in Cebu is completed. Built of reinforced concrete it is one of the early lighthouses of the American era.
Easter School classroom and dormitories are built.
Ynchausti Merchant House in Iloilo is built.
Zamboanga City Hall is completed and becomes the seat of the Moro Province, Department of Mindanao and Sulu, in 1914.
Manila Grand Opera House is used as the site of the first National Assembly.
First of the Baguio School’s buildings, later called Ogilby Hall is built. One of the oldest building structures in Baguio, it is marked by NHCP in 2011.
Aduana or Custom House in Cebu is built; its design is attributed to WIlliam Parsons.
Iloilo provincial jail is completed. In 2017, it undergoes restoration and redevelopment as the Iloilo branch of the National Museum.
The Laguna Capitol is completed.
The first permanent building of Teachers’ Camp in Baguio is raised; this is the mess hall.
Immaculate Conception Church and Ateneo de Zamboanga school buildings are completed.
The San Miguel Church in Manila is rebuilt in the Neoromanesque style.
Lourdes Grotto on Mirador Hill is constructed by Fr Jose Algue SJ, director of the Manila Observatory. Statue of Our Lady of Lourdes, carved and signed by Isabelo Tampinco, is placed in the grotto.
The Supreme Court on Taft Ave in Manila, designed by Parsons, is built.
Baguio Central School, established in 1898, is moved to a site near the Civic Center. The new building is in Neoclassical style with a Grecian portico.
Carnival Queen Theater is built in Baguio.
Nurses Home on Taft Ave, designed by Tomas Mapua (1888-1965) in Neorennaisance style, is completed.
The Neoclassical Sorsogon Capitol is completed.
Arcadio Arellano designs the Ariston Bautista Lin house in Quiapo.
Casino Español inaugurates a building on Taft Ave., designed by Arcadio and Juan Arellano.
Zamboanga Normal School, begun in 1917, is completed as the permanent home for the Provincial Normal School established in 1914.
The Legarda Elementary School in the French Renaissance style, noted for its Mansard roof and dormer windows, is completed. Its architect is Andres Luna de San Pedro, son of the painter Juan Luna.
Celso Ledesma Mansion in Iloilo City is completed in Beaux-Arts style with art deco touches. It is known for the eagles that decorate its fence.
The Javellana Bldg in Iloilo City, Neoclassical in style, is completed.
Casa Vallejo in Baguio opens, repurposing dormitories originally built for the workers who built Baguio.
The Negros Oriental Capitol in Dumaguete City is completed.
The Ledesma Residence in Jaro, Iloilo is constructed in the Neoclassical style around this time.

The Dominican architect, Roque Ruaño, completes the UST main building at España Ave. on a 10-hectare lot acquired earlier. The building is in Art Deco and is designed to survive earthquakes. (Photo from Archivo de la Universidad de Santo Tomas)
Palace Theater and the Dominican Sisters’ building, both in Iloilo, are constructed.
St Paul Manila’s Chapel of the Crucified Christ in Art Deco, designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro, is completed.
The Mercado-Marasigan residence in San Juan, Batangas, is completed.
Manila Jockey Club on Felix Huertas St is completed. Its architect is Juan Nakpil.
St. Clement’s Church in Iloilo in Art Deco is constructed under the Redemptorists.

Crystal Arcade in Art Deco, designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro, at Escolta is inaugurated. It is the first retail and office building to have underground parking. Photo: Prewar Crystal Arcade in Escolta, Manila
Ellinwood Church in Malate, Manila is constructed. It is in the Neogothic style favored by the Protestants.
Manila’s City Hall, begun in 1930 and designed by Toledo, is completed. Photo: Manila City Hall, ca 1950
St. Scholastica’s College on Pennsylvania (now Leon Guinto) St, designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro in the Neoromanesque style, is completed.

The Dr. Luis U. Santos residence in Malolos, Bulacan is completed. The house is eclectic in style but Art Deco dominates. The sala is dominated by a mural painting by Fernando Amorsolo. Photo: Art Deco Luis U. Santos Mansion, 2017 (Kiko del Rosario)
The American High Commisioner’s residence is constructed in Camp John Hay, Baguio. With independence it is turned over to the American ambassador. It is marked by NHCP in 2005.

The twin buildings of the Departments of Agriculture and Finance, facing Agrifina Circle, begun in 1930 and designed by Antonio Toledo, are completed. Photo: Dept of Finance Bldg, now National Museum of Anthropology in front of prewar Legislative Bldg, now National Museum of Fine Arts, ca 1960 (Edward Delos Santos/Pinoy Kollektor)
Loakan Airport in Baguio is completed.
The American Embassy along Roxas Blvd, Manila, designed by Juan Arellano, is constructed.
A new Iloilo City Hall, begun in 1933, is completed. It is designed by Juan Arellano in Neoclassical style, with sculptures by Francesco Monti.

The Lopez Streamline Moderne “boathouse,” designed by Fernando H. Ocampo, is completed. It is declared a heritage house by NHI in 2002 and marked in 2004. Restored, it is the regional training center of ABS-CBN Visayas.

The Meralco headquarters on San Marcelino St, Manila, built in Art Deco and designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro, is completed. Its facade is decorated with the sculpture, The Furies, by Francesco Monti. The building is now demolished.
The Cebu City Hall in the Federal style is completed.
Avenue Hotel and Theater is built on Rizal Ave in Manila.
The Magdalena Bldg in Iloilo, designed by Jose Tantoy Locsin, is built.
Admiral Apartments on Roxas Blvd, Manila, begun in 1938, is completed.
Ateneo de Naga main building in Naga City is completed, known for its Grecian temple entrance.
The Baguio General Hospital is rebuilt on a larger and grander scale, seven years after Pres Quezon promises to upgrade the hospital in 1937.
No major architectural projects are undertaken during World War II.

As a result of fires and bombardment, the southern side of Manila, especially Intramuros and the Taft Corridor buildings, are devastated. Manila is cited as the second most devastated city after World War II, second only to Warsaw.
Postwar reconstruction begins with funds coming from the War Damage Claims office and with material from World War II surplus.
The reconstruction of Assumption College on Herran St (Pedro Gil) begun in 1946 is completed, following the prewar Gothic style.
UCCP Church in Baguio is constructed. It is marked by NHCP in 2012.
Vision Theater in Cebu, begun in the 1930s, is completed under Engr Agustin Jereza.

The Victorias Chapel of St. Joseph the Worker in Victorias Sugar Central in Negros Occidental is completed. Ade Bethune designs the mosaics with assistance from local artisans and Alfonso Ossorio paints the murals. The mural in the sanctuary, The Last Judgment or more known as The Angry Christ, is controversial.
Melchor Hall in UP Diliman, QC, designed by Cesar H. Concio, is completed.
LJ Hormillosa Bldg in Iloilo is completed in the International style.
The National Press Club in Manila, designed by Angel Nakpil, is completed.

The eighth Manila Cathedral, begun in 1954, is inaugurated. Fernando H. Ocampo is head architect in charge of design and supervision. Teams of Italian and Filipino artists work on the interior. Stained glass design is by Galo Ocampo. Photo: Facade of Manila Cathedral, ca 1960 (Photo from CCP)
The World Health Organization Bldg, designed by Alfredo Luz, along Taft Ave, is completed.
Philippine Atomic Research Center, designed by Cresenciano de Castro, in UP Diliman, is completed.
The first Asian Development Bank (ADB) headquarters in Pasay City is completed. It is acquired by the Department of Foreign Affairs, when ADB moves to new quarters in 1986.
Hilton Hotel on UN Ave, designed by Carlos Arguelles and Welton Beckett, is inaugurated.
The Meralco Bldg on Ortigas Ave in Pasig City, designed by Jose Zaragoza, is completed.
The Iglesia Filipina Independiente’s Cathedral of the Santo Niño on Taft Ave, designed by Carlos Arguelles, is completed.

The Cultural Center of the Philippines, designed by Leandro Locsin, is inaugurated. Later, other buildings by Locsin will be built near it, like the Philippine International Convention Center and the Folk Arts Theater. (Photo by Akio Kawasumi in The Architecture of Leandro V. Locsin by Nicholas Polites, John Weatherhill Inc, 1977)
Benguet Mining Corporation Bldg in Pasig City, designed by Leandro Locsin, is completed. Its use of Benguet stone and step-like design evokes the Cordillera rice terraces.
The Central Bank of the Philippines in Manila and the Asian Institute of Management Bldg in Makati City, both designed by Gabriel Formoso, are completed.
Museo Iloilo is completed, designed by Sergio Peñasales.
Folk Arts Theater (later the Tanghalang Francisco Baltazar), designed by Leandro Locsin, is completed in time for the Miss Universe Pageant.
In preparation for the International Monetary Fund triennial meeting, high rise and five-star hotels are built. Roads are improved.
The Iglesia ni Cristo Main Temple in Quezon City is completed.
The second ADB headquarters, designed by Skidmore, Owings and Merrill (SOM) with partner Engracio L. Mariano and Associates, is completed.
The earthquake causes much damage. The Nevada Hotel and the Hyatt in Baguio collapse. The historic Dagupan Cathedral is damaged and roads in Pangasinan are impassable.

As a result of Republic Act 7227, the following government-owned areas are redeveloped as multiple use areas: Subic Naval Station, Subic Bay, Zambales; Clark Airbase, Pampanga; Camp John Hay, Baguio; and Fort Bonifacio, Taguig, Rizal.
Ateneo Professional Schools Makati City, designed by the firm of Francisco Mañosa, is completed. It shows the firm’s signature Neovernacular.
Tektite Towers and Renaissance Tower, both in Pasig City and both designed by Rogelio Villarosa, are completed.

World Exchange Tower in Binondo, Manila designed by American architect Michael Graves, is completed. The project ushers the trend of hiring well-known foreign architects for Philippine projects that strive to be “iconic.”
New construction experiences a slow down as a result of the crisis.
Pacific Plaza Tower in Fort Bonifacio, designed by Architectonica, is completed.
Essensa Towers in The Fort, Taguig City, designed by IM Pei (Pei, Cobb, Freed & Partners), is completed.
Cebu IT Park, begun in 2001, on the former Lahug Airport is completed.

A chapel for Southwestern University in Cebu, Ampoanan sa Kalinaw ug Kinaadman, designed by National Artist Napoleon Abueva, is completed. It is regarded more as a large sculptural work rather than a building.
The Medical City in Pasig City, designed by Archion, is completed.
Ayala Greenbelt is redesigned and remodelled by Recio and Casas to have more open spaces, trees and landscaped gardens.
SM Mall of Asia in the Pasay reclamation area and facing Manila Bay is completed.

Massive destruction happens to both modern and historic buildings in Cebu and Bohol. Santo Niño Basilica’s bell tower in Cebu collapses. Historic Bohol churches that were severely damaged include Baclayon, Loay, Loboc, Loon, and Maribojoc.
The Iglesia ni Cristo inaugurates the Philippine Arena in Ciudad Victoria, Bocaue and Santa Maria, Bulacan for the centennial celebration of INC.
The historic Cathedral of the Transfiguration of Palo, Leyte and the Church of La Inmaculada Concepcion in Guiuan, Samar are damaged by Typhoon Yolanda.
